 The Elysee Palace is seen before the investiture ceremony of Emmanuel Macron as French President in Paris, France, May 7, 2022. Macron won the second round of the election held on April 24 with an absolute majority of 18,768,638 votes (58.55 percent of the valid ballots cast). According to law, Macron's second term must begin no later than May 14. (Xinhua/Gao Jing)  Mayor of Paris Anne Hidalgo arrives at the Elysee Palace to attend the investiture ceremony of Emmanuel Macron as French President in Paris, France, May 7, 2022. Macron won the second round of the election held on April 24 with an absolute majority of 18,768,638 votes (58.55 percent of the valid ballots cast). According to law, Macron's second term must begin no later than May 14. (Xinhua/Gao Jing)  Former French President Francois Hollande arrives at the Elysee Palace to attend the investiture ceremony of Emmanuel Macron as French President in Paris, France, May 7, 2022. Macron won the second round of the election held on April 24 with an absolute majority of 18,768,638 votes (58.55 percent of the valid ballots cast). According to law, Macron's second term must begin no later than May 14. (Xinhua/Gao Jing)  Former French Prime Minister Jean-Pierre Raffarin arrives at the Elysee Palace to attend the investiture ceremony of Emmanuel Macron as French President in Paris, France, May 7, 2022. Macron won the second round of the election held on April 24 with an absolute majority of 18,768,638 votes (58.55 percent of the valid ballots cast). According to law, Macron's second term must begin no later than May 14. (Xinhua/Gao Jing)  Former French Prime Minister Jean-Pierre Raffarin arrives at the Elysee Palace to attend the investiture ceremony of Emmanuel Macron as French President in Paris, France, May 7, 2022. Macron won the second round of the election held on April 24 with an absolute majority of 18,768,638 votes (58.55 percent of the valid ballots cast). According to law, Macron's second term must begin n